hiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fontSize=11;fillColor=#c9b3dd;strokeColor=#4a2a78;fontColor=#201040;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="2172" y="2472" width="395" height="140" as="geometry"/></mxCell></object><object label="Early space expansion&lt;br&gt;re-arms the hazard&lt;br&gt;[1+2+5+6+7+8+15]&lt;br&gt;→ Shrimp Welfare Project&lt;br&gt;   66k lives-eq/$1k · 68% best&lt;br&gt;   runner-up Wild insects (humane pesticides) · 28%&lt;br&gt;(Daniel Deudney, Kelly &amp; Zach Weinersmith)" tooltip="&lt;b&gt;parochial + far_away_humans + animals_somewhat + future_humans_matter_with_discounting + no_discounting_future_humans + animals_matter_a_lot + suffering_focused + space_expansion_backfires&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The sweet-spot view: the capability that settles planets also moves asteroids and exports nationalism off-world (Deudney, Dark Skies), and genuinely decorrelated self-sufficient settlements are far further away than boosterism assumes (Weinersmiths, A City on Mars) — so below a large number of independent settlements, expansion ADDS anthropogenic risk, and accelerating it before geopolitics matures is net-negative. The perils window stays open far longer, the expected future shrinks, and x-risk work keeps its urgency but loses most of its astronomical multiplier. Mutually exclusive with the time-of-perils-exit reading. || Chain: 0 parochial → 1 far_away_humans → 2 animals_somewhat → 5 future_humans_matter_with_discounting → 6 no_discounting_future_humans → 7 animals_matter_a_lot → 8 suffering_focused → 15 space_expansion_backfires" link="https://www.squiggle-language.com/playground#code=eJy1WW1v2zgS%2FiuD4PbO7vlFkt%2BTywFp4%2BwWm3SLJL1i0RQuLdEWL5KoI6k43m72t%2B%2BQlGw5VlD1jP1SuBLnmWdeNcN8PQrogmSResMDenR81O3C6ekp3ArCElAcfEF%2BW%2BOPVQJ3mee4fVhxEQUPjK5g5c682WA2nI1m45k7gIZUPAV30NQQdwlCnUmZxaliPAE%2FRMRjcCAlgvshI5EGdCceuLAgYkZWZD0Ls5gksnjhAUlYTCI5kzymq5Co4s0AFpnKBM0FZjFRiorZiqlwFjDp8yxRLFkWx4eQ8PLz2Y50cWq0UZfDkVnENyrHILPFggojzv1M0mBjwABkSnw6o48p4qG1sznx7xdMUGncMCV